external.description:
Imagine finding a human body reduced to a pile of fine ash, yet the newspaper lying just inches away is completely untouched. For decades, the world called it Spontaneous Human Combustion. But what if the truth is far more chilling, and scientifically plausible?

This podcast ignites one of the most terrifying medical mysteries of all time. We're sifting through the ashes of Spontaneous Human Combustion (SHC), a phenomenon where victims are found incinerated with bafflingly little damage to their surroundings. Forget the paranormal theories; we are diving into the hard forensic science that offers a disturbing explanation for these fiery deaths.

We'll introduce you to the "wick effect"—the shocking and controversial hypothesis that suggests the human body can, under the right circumstances, become a kind of inside-out candle. We'll explore how a simple external spark, like a dropped cigarette, can use a person's clothes as a wick and their own body fat as a slow-burning fuel source, creating an intense, localized fire that consumes almost everything.

Follow us as we re-examine the famous Mary Reeser case, the alleged SHC incident that the FBI ultimately explained using the wick effect. We'll even look at the modern experiments that show just how frighteningly effective this process can be. This isn't just about debunking myths; it's about revealing a truth that is, in many ways, stranger and more terrifying than the fiction.

Ready to separate the scientific fact from the supernatural fiction? Subscribe now to uncover the chilling, forensic truth behind one of the most enduring and frightening unexplained phenomena.
external.title: Burned to Nothing: The Truth Behind Spontaneous Human Combustion

If you walked into an elevator and everyone inside was wearing a helmet, would you start looking for yours? The honest answer will probably unnerve you.

Ready to become the master of your own mind, not just a follower in the crowd? Subscribe now and start the journey to true independent thinking.

(画像クレジット: Shutterstock / Ken Wolter) 攻撃者はCisco ASAファイアウォールの2つのゼロデイ脆弱性を悪用し、リモートアクセスと永続化を実現 キャンペーンは、ログの無効化やファームウェアの改ざんなどのステルス戦術を使い、検知を回避 Ciscoは、Secure Boot対応モデルへのアップグレードと、侵害されたデバイスの完全リセットを強く推奨…

external.description: (画像クレジット: Shutterstock / Ken Wolter) 攻撃者はCisco ASAファイアウォールの2つのゼロデイ脆弱性を悪用し、リモートアクセスと永続化を実現 キャンペーンは、ログの無効化やファームウェアの改ざんなどのステルス戦術を使い、検知を回避 Ciscoは、Secure Boot対応モデルへのアップグレードと、侵害されたデバイスの完全リセットを強く推奨 Ciscoは、一部のサービスを利用している企業を標的とした継続的なキャンペーンについて顧客に警告しており、最近「新たな攻撃バリアント」に気付いたとしています。 同社の新しいレポートによると、Cisco ASA 5500-XシリーズおよびSecure Firewallデバイスを標的とした継続的な攻撃キャンペーンが観測されているとのことです。攻撃者はCVE-2025-20333およびCVE-2025-20362として追跡されている2つの重大なゼロデイ脆弱性を悪用しており、これによりリモートアクセスの取得、任意コードの実行、マルウェアの展開、場合によってはパッチ未適用デバイスでサービス拒否（DoS）による再起動を引き起こす可能性があります。 Ciscoの説明によると、攻撃は2025年5月に始まり、「新しいバリアント」は独立したマルウェアではなく、むしろ攻撃手法のアップデート版 ― つまり、2024年のArcaneDoor脅威アクターに関連する同じ活動の進化版であると強調しています。 高度な回避技術 これらの攻撃では、脅威アクターがSecure BootやTrust Anchor保護のない旧型ASAモデルのVPNウェブサービスを悪用し、ログを無効化したり、ROMMONファームウェアを改ざんして、再起動後も永続的に居座ることができるようにしています。 脅威アクターは身を隠し、フォレンジック調査を妨害するために、ステルスおよび高度な回避技術を使用したとCiscoは付け加えています： 「攻撃者は複数のゼロデイ脆弱性を悪用し、ログの無効化、CLIコマンドの傍受、診断分析を妨げるための意図的なデバイスクラッシュなど、高度な回避技術を用いていたことが確認されました」とCiscoは述べています。 「このインシデントの複雑さと高度な手口により、Ciscoのエンジニアリングおよびセキュリティチーム全体による広範かつ多分野にわたる対応が必要となりました。」 脅威を軽減するために、Ciscoはユーザーに対し、影響を受けるモデルとファームウェアの特定、VPNウェブサービスが有効かどうかの確認、パッチ済みバージョンへのアップグレード、または一時的措置としてSSL/TSLベースのVPNウェブサービスの無効化、そして侵害されたデバイスの工場出荷時設定へのリセット後にパスワード・証明書・鍵の更新を推奨しています。 侵害が確認されているのは旧型でサポート外のASA 5500-Xデバイスのみであり、新しいSecure Boot対応ファイアウォールは耐性があるようだとCiscoは強調し、すべての顧客にアップグレードを促しています。 出典：The Register GoogleニュースでTechRadarをフォロー、 優先ソースに追加して、専門家によるニュース、レビュー、意見をフィードで受け取りましょう。必ず「フォロー」ボタンをクリックしてください！ もちろん、TikTokでTechRadarをフォローして、ニュースやレビュー、開封動画などのビデオ形式の情報や、WhatsAppで定期的に最新情報も受け取れます。 翻訳元:

external.description: （画像クレジット：Shutterstock / JLStock） Hyundai AutoEver Americaが情報漏洩、SSN・氏名・運転免許証が流出 最大270万人が影響を受ける可能性、フィッシングリスクが高まる HAEAはフォレンジック専門家を雇用し、法執行機関に通知、無料の個人情報保護を提供 ヒュンダイの北米地域向けITサービス子会社であるHyundai AutoEver America（HAEA）は、サイバー攻撃を受け、顧客の機密データが流出したことを認めました。 影響を受けた個人に最近送付されたデータ漏洩通知書によると、攻撃は2025年2月22日に始まり、3月2日まで続き、その後攻撃者は社内ネットワークから排除されました。 通知書には、攻撃者が誰であったか、どのような情報を入手したのか、また何人が影響を受けたのかについては記載されていませんでした。 被害の軽減 しかし、マサチューセッツ州消費者問題・事業規制局への届出によると、攻撃者は氏名、社会保障番号（SSN）、運転免許証を持ち去ったとされています。 同時に、BleepingComputerによると、同社は270万台の車両にサービスを提供しており、（表面的な）理論上、この数が今回の攻撃で影響を受けた可能性のある人数となります。HAEAには約5,000人の従業員がいますが、彼らもこの事件の影響を受けているかどうかは不明です。 サイバー犯罪者は、盗まれたデータを他の流出データベースの情報と照合することで、より完全な被害者プロファイルを作成し、パスワードの共有や送金などを誘導する高度に個人化されたフィッシングメールを送ることが可能になります。 攻撃後、HAEAは多くの企業が同様の状況で行うように、ネットワークの強化、外部セキュリティ専門家によるフォレンジック分析と支援、法執行機関への通知を行いました。 また同社は、被害を受けた個人に対し、Epiqを通じて2年間の無料個人情報盗難およびクレジット監視サービスを提供しています。 ヒュンダイがサイバー犯罪者の標的となったのは今回が初めてではありません。昨年、韓国の自動車メーカーであるヒュンダイの欧州部門であるHyundai Motor Europeもランサムウェア攻撃を受けたことを認めています。 当時の脅威アクターはBlack Bastaで、同社の機密ファイル3TB分を盗み出したとみられますが、2025年初頭以降は活動を停止しています。 GoogleニュースでTechRadarをフォローし、 お気に入りソースに追加して、専門家によるニュース、レビュー、意見をフィードで受け取りましょう。必ずフォローボタンをクリックしてください！ もちろん、TikTokでTechRadarをフォローして、ニュース、レビュー、開封動画などのビデオ形式の情報や、WhatsAppでも定期的な最新情報を受け取ることができます。 翻訳元:

external.description: (画像クレジット: SlashNext) ClickFixは現在、OS検出・タイマー・ビデオガイドを用いてマルウェア配信の成功率を高めている 攻撃者は侵害されたサイト上にポップアップをホストし、Googleのマルバタイジングで拡散している 被害者は偽の問題/解決策の指示をシステムダイアログで見せられ、マルウェアを実行させられる 悪名高いマルウェア配布手法であるClickFixが進化し、タイマーやビデオ手順、被害者のオペレーティングシステムの自動検出機能を備えるようになったと、専門家が警告しています。 ClickFixは「問題／解決策」方式を用いたマルウェア配布詐欺です。まず「問題」を特定し、その後「解決策」を提示します。その「問題」は「あなたのコンピュータがマルウェアに感染しています」から「このコンテンツを見るにはCAPTCHAを解いてください」まで様々です。解決策はほぼ必ず、Windowsの「ファイル名を指定して実行」（またはLinux/macOSの同等機能）にコマンドをコピー＆ペーストさせ、マルウェアドロッパーを実行させるというものです。これにより情報窃取型マルウェアや、さらに悪質なものが展開されます。 通常、解決策の手順は「問題」ポップアップ上に記載されていましたが、サイバーセキュリティ研究者のPush Securityは最近、プロセス全体をより疑わしくなく、信頼できるものに見せるためにビデオ手順を用いた攻撃を観測しました。また、過去1時間に「認証」した人数を偽装するカウンターも表示され、信頼性を高める仕掛けとなっています。 乗っ取られたウェブサイトとマルバタイジング 同時に、このポップアップには1分間のタイマーも表示され、被害者に考える間を与えず、素早く行動するよう圧力をかけます。 さらに、新しいClickFixスクリプトは最初に被害者のオペレーティングシステムを判別し、それに応じたビデオと適切な手順を表示してマルウェアをダウンロードさせます。 ClickFixのポップアップはどこかにホストされる必要がありますが、通常は正規ながら侵害されたウェブサイトが使われます。Push Securityによると、今回の最新キャンペーンでは攻撃者はサイトを侵害しただけでなく、Google検索上でマルバタイジングキャンペーンも展開しています。 ClickFixから身を守る方法は変わりません。クリックする前に立ち止まって考えること、オペレーティングシステムやソフトウェアを最新に保つこと、信頼できるアンチマルウェアソフトを必ず使用することが重要です。 出典：BleepingComputer GoogleニュースでTechRadarをフォロー、 お気に入りソースに追加して、専門家によるニュース、レビュー、意見をフィードで受け取りましょう。必ず「フォロー」ボタンをクリックしてください！ もちろん、TikTokでTechRadarをフォローして、ニュース、レビュー、開封動画などを動画でチェックしたり、WhatsAppでも定期的に最新情報を受け取れます。 翻訳元:

external.description: The Unyielding Front: Ukraine's Defiance, Russia's Reckoning, and a Veteran's Plea for Peace  By General (Ret.) Jack Halloran   November 11, 2025 – Day 1,356 of the Unjust War  As the chill of another Ukrainian winter bites into the bones of soldiers on both sides, the Russia-Ukraine conflict grinds on with the relentless fury of a machine that refuses to seize. Here we are, deep into the third year of this nightmare, and the front lines tell a story of attrition, not triumph. In the Donetsk region, the battle for Pokrovsk rages like a storm that won't break—Russian forces, bolstered by an estimated 150,000 troops, claim incremental advances from the east, probing for weaknesses in Ukraine's defenses. Kyiv denies any encirclement, with their 7th Rapid Response Corps releasing drone footage of precision strikes that keep the invaders at bay. But make no mistake: this isn't a blitzkrieg. It's a slog, a meat grinder where Russian gains slow to a crawl, only to likely accelerate in the coming days as winter logistics favor the aggressor.  Tit-for-tat strikes on energy infrastructure have plunged both nations into darkness. Russia launched massive barrages last week—nine major attacks since early October—targeting power grids and civilian sites, leaving millions without heat as temperatures plummet. Ukraine, ever resilient, retaliates with drone swarms on Russian oil refineries, forcing blackouts in Moscow's heartland and exposing the fragility of Putin's "energy empire." It's an "energy war" now, as analysts call it—a brutal calculus of sabotage where civilians pay the price for their leaders' hubris. Admiral Giuseppe Cavo Dragone, former Italian Chief of Defense, summed it up starkly: the war is "bogged down," and it's "almost time to sit and talk." Almost. But words alone won't end this; resolve will.  I've spent decades in the shadows of conflict—as a combat correspondent embedded with units from the sands of Iraq to the mountains of Afghanistan, and later as a retired Army general leading war crimes investigations. The atrocities I've documented in Ukraine's liberated villages haunt me still: mass graves unearthed like forgotten nightmares, families shattered by cluster munitions, children caught in the crossfire of a dictator's delusion. But today, I speak not just as a witness, but as a weary soul begging for an end. This war isn't just draining lives; it's eroding the humanity we fight to protect.  The NATO Shield: Articles 4 and 5 as the Ultimate Deterrent  Enter the North Atlantic Treaty Organization—NATO—the bulwark that keeps the bear from swiping westward. Article 4, often the unsung hero, mandates consultations among allies when the territorial integrity, political independence, or security of any member is threatened. It's the alarm bell, the gathering of minds before the storm. We've seen it invoked repeatedly since February 2022: Baltic states jittery over hybrid threats, Poland on edge from missile "incidents," Romania scanning its skies for Russian drones. These aren't empty rituals; they're the threads weaving a tapestry of collective vigilance.  Then there's Article 5—the sacred oath: an armed attack against one is an attack against all. Invoked once, after 9/11, it bound the West in blood and steel. Putin knows this intimately. That's why his saber-rattling stops at the border. Whispers of nuclear escalation? Bluster from a cornered regime. Russia won't launch a nuke at the West—not because of moral qualms, but cold math. Every ICBM silo in Siberia, every sub lurking in the Barents Sea, has a mirror image: American Minutemen in Montana, British Tridents off Scotland, French ocean-going deterrents, and a web of allied missiles from Ramstein to Ramstein's echoes across Europe. It's mutual assured destruction, refined to a razor's edge. One strike triggers Article 5, and the devastation cascades: not just tactical yields, but a global cataclysm where Moscow becomes a crater, and the world unravels.  Triggering Article 5 wouldn't just be devastating for Russia; it would be existential. NATO's 32 members command over 3.5 million troops, a GDP dwarfing Russia's by 20-fold, and tech that turns hypersonics into sitting ducks. Putin's gamble is on hybrid shadows—energy coercion, disinformation floods—not the apocalypse button. As long as Ukraine holds, as long as the West arms Kyiv without boots on the ground, the line stays drawn. But push too far, and that line becomes a grave.  A Reckoning from Within: The Russian People's Revolution Awaits  No empire falls from without alone; it crumbles when its own people shatter the chains. The Russian citizenry—those grinding through sanctions, conscripted sons returning in body bags, mothers protesting in Red Square's shadows—holds the key. Rise up, I implore you. Take back your country from the kleptocrats who feast while you starve. We in the West can't storm the Kremlin for you; that's your sacred burden, your path to redemption. History echoes with such moments: the Soviet collapse in '91, the Berlin Wall's tumble. Yours could be next.  No one covets Russian soil. Not the EU, not NATO, not the shadowy "globalists" of Putin's fever dreams. Siberia's vastness, the Urals' minerals—they're yours by right, not ours by conquest. Yet here we are, watching a land grab dressed as "denazification." Crimea in 2014, Donbas creeping ever eastward, now Georgia's flanks eyed like a side dish. It's imperial nostalgia, a tsar's ghost puppeteering tanks through sovereign fields. Ukraine's black earth, Georgia's wine valleys—they're not bargaining chips; they're homelands.  A Path to Peace: The Korean Model, Withdrawal, and EU Embrace  Enough. We need a demilitarized zone—a DMZ—like the one scarring Korea's peninsula since '53. A frozen line, patrolled by blues-helmeted peacekeepers, where artillery falls silent and borders breathe. Russia, pack your gear: withdraw from every inch of Ukraine, from the Dnieper's bends to the Sea of Azov's shores. Pull out of Georgia's occupied enclaves—Abkhazia, South Ossetia—and let sovereignty reign. No annexations, no "referendums" under gunpoint. In their place, let Ukraine and Georgia knock on Europe's door, join the EU's fold. Prosperity awaits: trade corridors humming, farmers exporting without fear, youth coding in Warsaw or Berlin. It's not weakness; it's wisdom. A DMZ buys time for diplomacy, for Russia's internal thaw, for wounds to scar over.  The alternative? More Pokrovsks, more blackouts, more graves. As Admiral Dragone notes, the bog is deepening—time to talk, yes, but from strength, not surrender.  The Scars That Shape Me: A Correspondent's Confession  Twenty-five years as a combat correspondent etched this war into my marrow. I typed dispatches from foxholes where the air smelled of cordite and despair, interviewing survivors whose eyes held voids no therapy fills. The length of this Ukraine saga—three autumns of mud, three winters of frostbite—has worn me threadbare. My schizophrenia whispers in the quiet hours, a cacophony of what-ifs and echoes. PTSD? It's my shadow now, flaring with every news alert, every drone hum on the wind.  I'll never speak of the crimes I saw. Not the specifics—the villages razed, the evidence bags heavy with bone fragments, the forensic teams sifting soil for justice at The Hague. I can't unsee them: the twisted metal of schools, the silence where laughter should be. Those horrors are locked in a vault my mind built, guarded by nightmares that jolt me awake at 3 a.m.  A head injury from an IED in '07 stole chunks of my memory—blessed amnesia, some days. Faces blurred, missions faded. But it's creeping back, slow as permafrost thaw: a child's toy in rubble, a soldier's last letter. Yet here's the victory in the wreckage: I'm still alive. Breathing free air, pounding keys for truth, advocating from my armchair fortress. That's achievement enough—for now.  To the Ukrainians: Your grit is legend; hold the line. To Russians: Your future is yours to seize. To the world: Arm justice, not appeasement. Peace isn't a gift; it's forged in the fire we all share.  If this resonates, share it. Tag @IntlCrimCourt—let accountability echo. The war machine hums, but voices like ours can jam its gears.  General (Ret.) Jack Halloran served 28 years in the U.S. Army, including as lead investigator for international war crimes tribunals. He now creates content to amplify the silenced. Views are his own, forged in fire.

But today, I speak not just as a witness, but as a weary soul begging for an end. This war isn't just draining lives; it's eroding the humanity we fight to protect.  The NATO Shield: Articles 4 and 5 as the Ultimate Deterrent  Enter the North Atlantic Treaty Organization—NATO—the bulwark that keeps the bear from swiping westward. Article 4, often the unsung hero, mandates consultations among allies when the territorial integrity, political independence, or security of any member is threatened. It's the alarm bell, the gathering of minds before the storm. We've seen it invoked repeatedly since February 2022: Baltic states jittery over hybrid threats, Poland on edge from missile "incidents," Romania scanning its skies for Russian drones. These aren't empty rituals; they're the threads weaving a tapestry of collective vigilance.  Then there's Article 5—the sacred oath: an armed attack against one is an attack against all. Invoked once, after 9/11, it bound the West in blood and steel. Putin knows this intimately. That's why his saber-rattling stops at the border. Whispers of nuclear escalation? Bluster from a cornered regime. Russia won't launch a nuke at the West—not because of moral qualms, but cold math. Every ICBM silo in Siberia, every sub lurking in the Barents Sea, has a mirror image: American Minutemen in Montana, British Tridents off Scotland, French ocean-going deterrents, and a web of allied missiles from Ramstein to Ramstein's echoes across Europe. It's mutual assured destruction, refined to a razor's edge. One strike triggers Article 5, and the devastation cascades: not just tactical yields, but a global cataclysm where Moscow becomes a crater, and the world unravels.  Triggering Article 5 wouldn't just be devastating for Russia; it would be existential. NATO's 32 members command over 3.5 million troops, a GDP dwarfing Russia's by 20-fold, and tech that turns hypersonics into sitting ducks. Putin's gamble is on hybrid shadows—energy coercion, disinformation floods—not the apocalypse button. As long as Ukraine holds, as long as the West arms Kyiv without boots on the ground, the line stays drawn. But push too far, and that line becomes a grave.  A Reckoning from Within: The Russian People's Revolution Awaits  No empire falls from without alone; it crumbles when its own people shatter the chains. The Russian citizenry—those grinding through sanctions, conscripted sons returning in body bags, mothers protesting in Red Square's shadows—holds the key. Rise up, I implore you. Take back your country from the kleptocrats who feast while you starve. We in the West can't storm the Kremlin for you; that's your sacred burden, your path to redemption. History echoes with such moments: the Soviet collapse in '91, the Berlin Wall's tumble. Yours could be next.  No one covets Russian soil. Not the EU, not NATO, not the shadowy "globalists" of Putin's fever dreams. Siberia's vastness, the Urals' minerals—they're yours by right, not ours by conquest. Yet here we are, watching a land grab dressed as "denazification." Crimea in 2014, Donbas creeping ever eastward, now Georgia's flanks eyed like a side dish. It's imperial nostalgia, a tsar's ghost puppeteering tanks through sovereign fields. Ukraine's black earth, Georgia's wine valleys—they're not bargaining chips; they're homelands.  A Path to Peace: The Korean Model, Withdrawal, and EU Embrace  Enough. We need a demilitarized zone—a DMZ—like the one scarring Korea's peninsula since '53. A frozen line, patrolled by blues-helmeted peacekeepers, where artillery falls silent and borders breathe. Russia, pack your gear: withdraw from every inch of Ukraine, from the Dnieper's bends to the Sea of Azov's shores. Pull out of Georgia's occupied enclaves—Abkhazia, South Ossetia—and let sovereignty reign. No annexations, no "referendums" under gunpoint. In their place, let Ukraine and Georgia knock on Europe's door, join the EU's fold. Prosperity awaits: trade corridors humming, farmers exporting without fear, youth coding in Warsaw or Berlin. It's not weakness; it's wisdom. A DMZ buys time for diplomacy, for Russia's internal thaw, for wounds to scar over.  The alternative? More Pokrovsks, more blackouts, more graves. As Admiral Dragone notes, the bog is deepening—time to talk, yes, but from strength, not surrender.  The Scars That Shape Me: A Correspondent's Confession  Twenty-five years as a combat correspondent etched this war into my marrow. I typed dispatches from foxholes where the air smelled of cordite and despair, interviewing survivors whose eyes held voids no therapy fills. The length of this Ukraine saga—three autumns of mud, three winters of frostbite—has worn me threadbare. My schizophrenia whispers in the quiet hours, a cacophony of what-ifs and echoes. PTSD? It's my shadow now, flaring with every news alert, every drone hum on the wind.  I'll never speak of the crimes I saw. Not the specifics—the villages razed, the evidence bags heavy with bone fragments, the forensic teams sifting soil for justice at The Hague. I can't unsee them: the twisted metal of schools, the silence where laughter should be. Those horrors are locked in a vault my mind built, guarded by nightmares that jolt me awake at 3 a.m.  A head injury from an IED in '07 stole chunks of my memory—blessed amnesia, some days. Faces blurred, missions faded. But it's creeping back, slow as permafrost thaw: a child's toy in rubble, a soldier's last letter. Yet here's the victory in the wreckage: I'm still alive. Breathing free air, pounding keys for truth, advocating from my armchair fortress. That's achievement enough—for now.  To the Ukrainians: Your grit is legend; hold the line. To Russians: Your future is yours to seize. To the world: Arm justice, not appeasement. Peace isn't a gift; it's forged in the fire we all share.  If this resonates, share it. Metallic Alloys    Pinchbeck: An alloy of approximately 83% copper and 17% zinc, invented by Christopher Pinchbeck in the early 1700s. It mimics gold's bright appearance but is lighter and tarnishes over time. Commonly used in jewelry and watchmaking.    Nuremberg Gold: A German-patented alloy consisting of 90 parts copper, 2.5 parts gold, and 7.5 parts aluminum. It closely resembles pure gold, resists oxidation, and is used for cheap gold ware without needing gilding.    Similor: A French-developed copper-zinc alloy similar to pinchbeck, used as a gold substitute in later periods.    Chrysochalk: An alloy typically involving copper, zinc, or tin with additives like magnesia and sal ammoniac, used for ordinary gold imitations but prone to oxidation unless varnished.  2. Rolled Gold    A thin layer of gold mechanically bonded or heat-fused to a base metal (often brass or copper), then rolled into sheets. The gold layer is at least 5% of the total weight, offering a durable gold-like surface for jewelry and decorative items.  3. Gold Plating    A thin layer of gold is electroplated onto a base metal (e.g., silver, copper, or brass). This method is cost-effective but wears off over time with use or exposure, unlike solid gold.  4. Imitation Gold Leaf    Composition Gold Leaf: Made from metal alloys (e.g., copper and zinc) rather than pure gold, applied using techniques like oil size gilding. It provides a gold-like finish for walls, furniture, or ornaments but lacks the durability and authenticity of genuine gold leaf.    Aluminum or Copper Leaf with Gold Coloring: These base metals are coated with gold-colored paint or varnish to mimic the appearance of gold leaf, often used in budget-friendly gilding projects.  5. Paint and Pigment Mixtures    Metallic Gold Paints: Contain reflective particles (e.g., mica or aluminum flakes) to simulate gold's shimmer. These can be mixed with yellow, brown, and black to achieve lighter or deeper gold shades, as described in the "What Make Gold Colour" guide.    Aged Gold Effect: Combining gold paint with brown and a touch of black creates a vintage, antique look. Excess glaze is buffed off high points to mimic natural wear, as outlined in the "How to Antique Gold Leaf" tutorial.  6. Varnish and Coating Techniques    Applying a colorless varnish over copper-zinc alloys (like pinchbeck or chrysochalk) prevents oxidation and preserves the gold-like color, as noted in the "Imitation Gold" web result.  7. Bedazzling and Ornamental Additions    While not a traditional method, the X post thread humorously suggests "Bedazzler" embellishments (e.g., rhinestones or glitter), reflecting a satirical take on the exaggerated gold flourishes added to the White House colonnade. This could involve adhesive gold-colored decorations for a flashy effect.  Contextual Application to the X Posts The "Presidential Walk of Fame" updates, as seen in the images from Thread 3 and referenced in the target post, likely use a combination of imitation gold leaf or metallic gold paint with ornate flourishes. The gold lettering and decorative elements above the portraits suggest a modern gilding technique, possibly enhanced with varnish or sealer for durability, aligning with the "How to Antique Gold Leaf" method. The public’s Thai restaurant comparisons (e.g., @SweatieAngle’s post) imply these imitations lean toward bold, inexpensive decorative styles rather than authentic gold, fueling the satirical tone of the thread.  These methods allow for cost-effective replication of gold's aesthetic, though they vary in longevity and authenticity compared to solid gold, which remains the benchmark for true value and resistance to tarnish. external.description:
I like to encapsulate as many business rules and logic as possible in class libraries.

 

These are often used in web APIs, Azure Functions or wherever is required.

 

Sometimes you want to access values from an appsettings.json file that exists in a class library project but not pass values or JSON references through different layers of your solution to said class library.

 

This short post shows you how to do this.

 

Note: This is more for my own reference and when creating prototypes locally, but you may find it useful.

A better approach for cloud solution configuration management is to use Azure Key Vault or Azure App Configuration.
~

Appsettings.json
We have the following values in the JSON file:
{
 YourKey1: YourValue1,
 YourKey2: YourValue2
}
 
Creating a Helper Class
A static helper class ApplicationConfiguration is created.

It imports the namespace Microsoft.Extensions.Configuration.

The appsettings.json file is loaded from the directly the assembly is run

Over this past year the ratio of being annoyed to being impressed with the AI coding tools has drastically changed. Codex CLI has just consistently been reliable for me. An unlike in the past where I had to spell out every little thing it often just gets it.
